Ford GoBike System Data¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This data set includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

In [2]:
# import all packages and set plots to be embedded inline

Gather Data¶

Gathering Data of ford gobike bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area and we added data for chicago and will combine them on one dataframe

the first data set of san francisco downloaded from udacity resources

second dataset of chicago download from https://www.bikeshare.com/data/

In [3]:
# load in the dataset into a pandas dataframe, print statistics
bike = pd.read_csv('ford-gobike/201902-fordgobike-tripdata.csv')

Creating the file we'll be storing our data in (this cell changed to markdown as the file created already and when we try to recreate it gets error because it already exist)

os.makedirs('ford-gobike')

Downloading all the files for Chicago city¶

urls = ['https://divvy-tripdata.s3.amazonaws.com/Divvy_Trips_2019_Q1.zip']

for url in urls: response = requests.get(url) zip_file = ZipFile(BytesIO(response.content)) zip_file.extractall('ford-gobike')

In [4]:
# get data file names
path =r'ford-gobike'
filenames = glob.glob(path + "/*.csv")

dfs = []
for filename in filenames:
    dfs.append(pd.read_csv(filename))

# Concatenate all data into one DataFrame
gobike = pd.concat(dfs, ignore_index=True)

tidness and quality issue found¶

  • in columns [start_time, end_time] their type need to be changed from strings to datetime type for easier analysis
  • create new column for member ages by taking the birth date and subtract it from the year of the data set 2019 and put it in new column
  • fill the null values in member ages with the average age of the members
  • remove null values on other columns that may impact the analysis like the gender, user type, etc

issue¶

Adding Age Groupings¶

add ages to groups to use in eploratory and explanatory visualization

code¶

In [16]:
# create bins for member ages
age_bins = [0, 19, 29, 39, 49, 59,
            69, 79, 89, 99]
age_labels = ['10 - 19', '20 - 29', '30 - 39', '40 - 49', '50 - 59',
              '60 - 69', '70 - 79', '80 - 89', '90 - 99']

gobike['age_group'] = pd.cut(gobike['member_age'], bins = age_bins, labels = age_labels, right = False)

def blank(df):
    if pd.isna(df).sum().sum():
        return df.dropna(axis=0)
    return df

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 174877 unique bike share entries in the data set mostly are categorical variables

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm intersted in figuring out what features are impacting the rides of bikes

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think the dates and address where the ride started from will have the highest impact on the frequency of the rides

  • Member Year of Birth
  • Member Gender
  • User Type (Subscriber or Customer Subscriber = Member or Customer = Casual)
  • Trip Duration(in seconds)
  • Bike ID
  • Start Time and Date
  • End Time and Date
  • Start Station ID
  • End Station ID
  • Start Station Name
  • End Station Name
  • End Station Latitude
  • End Station Longitude
  • Start Station Latitude
  • Start Station Longitude

Questions to be answered¶

  • How long does the average trip take?
  • When are most trips taken in terms of time of day, day of the week, or month of the year?
  • is there a relationship between age and duration?
  • Does the above depend on if a user is a subscriber or customer or a male or female?

investigate distributions of individual variables.

  • How long does the average trip take?

I'll start by looking at the distribution of the main variable of interest: duration_sec.

In [48]:
# Converting the trip durations from seconds to minutes 

gobike['duration_min'] = gobike['duration_sec'] / 60

binedges = 10**np.arange(0 , 3+0.1 , 0.1)
ticks =  [ 0.1 , 0.3 , 1 , 3, 10, 30, 100, 300]
labels = ['{}'.format(v) for v in ticks]
plt.hist(data = gobike , x = 'duration_min' , bins = binedges);
plt.xticks(ticks,labels);
plt.title('Distribution of various Trip Duration')
plt.xlabel('Duration in Minutes');
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.xscale('log');

as per above plots average durations is most probably around 10 minutes

# is member age and gender related to the trip duration?
gender_markers = [['Male', 's'],['Female', 'o'],['Other', 'v']]

for gender, marker in gender_markers:
    df_gender = gobike[gobike['member_gender'] == gender]
    plt.scatter(df_gender['member_age'], df_gender['duration_min'], marker = marker, alpha=0.50)
plt.legend(['Male','Female','Other'])
plt.axis([10, 90, 0, 1000 ])
plt.xlabel('Age (year)')
plt.ylabel('Duration (min)')
plt.show()
  • This plot does not show quit a clear picture, lets seperate all three genders into different graphs.
In [68]:
gobike['age'] = gobike['member_age']
genders = sb.FacetGrid(data = gobike, col = 'member_gender', col_wrap = 3, height = 6,
                 xlim = [10, 80], ylim = [0, 1000])
genders.map(plt.scatter, 'age', 'duration_min', alpha=0.50)
genders.set_xlabels('Age (year)')
genders.set_ylabels('Duration (min)')

plt.show()

As showing there is huge impact from gender on the trip duration

  • males mostly using bikes for duration except for males between 20 and 60 they have higher duration
  • Females are using bikes the same but there is huge difference in age of 60 between females and males as it hugely drops(consider that on previous pie chart the percentage of females 22.9% only so they are not the same numbers as males so need more information for it)
